  "title": "The Meaning of Research",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6001599a3902db5b",
      "text": "The counterpart to research is \"court reporting\" ([https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hofberichterstattung Hofberichterstattung]). Here, the journalist acts in the role of the letter carrier, who forwards the messages of the senders to the recipients without being seen. Of course, the good letter carrier is not only reliable, but also discreet; he maintains the secrecy of the letter and has no knowledge of the statements of the messages to be delivered. The court reporters behave in a very similar way. They would probably make good letter carriers."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "518e88b6ac7e0052",
      "text": "The mass media are the sheer opposite of the letter carrier, who transmits personal messages under the protection of privacy. The communications made public are not intended to be private, but rather to be generally noteworthy and valid. Publicly transmitted information is also received quite differently by the recipients than private information: Probably the majority of readers assume that the journalists will check the content of the information. The court reporter therefore acts in a completely un-journalistic manner: because he publishes everything unchecked as it is presented to him, he does not act as a bearer of the public, but privatizes the public in the service of the sender. The journalist has to take public responsibility for the content of his news. There is a media law dimension and, above all, a journalistic dimension. The following three main characteristics can be used to define this responsibility from a journalistic point of view:"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5742d3a256e1ccab",
      "text": "**Significance**: Is the information of general importance, does it bring out the important aspects of the event, and/or is it of interest to at least part of my readership?\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "36c87c8d92cbff85",
      "text": "**Validity**: Is the information correct, i.e. are the statements made actually true with regard to the facts they report? (colloquially speaking, the information should be \"true\").\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e09785c938418b87",
      "text": "**Comprehensibility**: Is the information sufficiently dense and comprehensive to be able to understand what has happened, the connections and, if possible, the meaning? (The linguistic comprehensibility of the information is expected anyway).\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a9f8787871adfd7d",
      "text": "Each of the three requirements leads to [[Research]]. And since all three are actually to be met by the journalist, research work is indispensable."
    }
